The trading rule considered in this study is based on a simple market timing strategy, consisting of investing total
funds in either the stock market or a risk free security. This rule is used to classify each day into periods ‚Äúin‚Äù (earning
the market return) or ‚Äúout‚Äù of the market (earning the risk-free rate of return). The trading strategy speciÔ¨Åes the
position to be taken the following day, given the current position and the ‚Äúbuy‚Äù or ‚Äúsell‚Äù signals generated by rule.
On the one hand, if the current state is ‚Äúin‚Äù (i. e., the investor is holding shares in the market) and the share prices are
expected to fall on the basis of a sell signal generated by the rule (S (Œò)t ‚â§ 0), then shares are sold and the proceeds
from the sale are invested in the risk free security [earning the risk-free rate of return r f (t)]. On the other hand, if the
current state is ‚Äúout‚Äù and the rule indicates that share market prices will increase in the near future, the rule returns a
‚Äúbuy‚Äù signal S (Œò)t > 0) and, as a result, the risk free security is sold and shares are bought [earning the market rate
of return rm (t)]. Finally, in the remaining two cases [stock held and buy signal; stock sold and sell signal], the current
state is preserved.
